{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_quercitron_ver01/data/sn83045774/00271744109/1920111901/0565.xml":{"full_text":"|j\"\" Our Circular on\nSouthern Railway\nand\nPacific Gas Electric\nanalyzes the prospects of\nthese two companies as\na Railroad and a Public\nUtility representative of\nthose properties which\nshould benefit by their\nchanged status under pres\neni conuiuona.\nAsk for Circular KAO\nA. A.Housman Co.\nMew York Stock Hack.\n(I Mew York Cotton Back.\nM.T.Coffee k Suyar Exeh.\nNew York Produce Exch\nCbicaro Board of Trade.\nAeeoclatn Member* of\nLiverpool Cotton Aso'n.\no Broad Street, New York\nBranch Office*:\n25 West 334 St. Mew York City.\nLiberty Itnildinc, Philadelphia\nAmsterdam Hollnnd\nA Selection\nof Bonds\nWe have prepared a\ncircular describing five\nbonds which we have\nselected from three different\nclasses of securities.\n\"V\nAt least one of these\nbonds should meet the\nrequirements of any investor.\nWe shall be\npleased to send this circular\nupon request.\nAtl( for Circular No. 12\nGraham,Parsons Co.\n435 Chestnut St. 30 Pine St.\nPhiladelphia New York\nJohn 5727-30\nChicago, St. Paul\nMinneapolis Omaha\nRailway Company\n5s, March 1, 1930\nThe Omaha it controlled through ownership\nof majority of stock by Chicago and\nNorthwestern Ry. and forms part of\none of our strongest railroad systems.\nSold at 105'/2 in 1912.\nTo net 7.30%\nPrittrp Sc 3?fjitplg\nKstnhRshed 1S7S.\nMembers Alew York Slock Exchange\n52 Broadway Tel. Broa 1 6323\nPrisate wires to Phila., Boston,\nBaltimore, Hichmond, Neir Haven,\nTO YIELD\n83/4%\nAn unusually attractive\nand well-seasoned\nClosed First Mortgage\nGold Note In denominations\nof $100, $300\nand $1,000, the Security\nof whl ch is over\nSeven times the\namount of the issue.\nEarnings over Six\ntimes the Interest requirements\ntwo shares\nof Bonus Common\nstock with each $1,000\nnote.\nCircular upon request.\nMARTIN CO.\nhntablinhed 1847\nMembers New York Stock Exchange\n111 Rm.rlw.v V L.\nIll Via j\nSinger Mfg.\nEastman Kodak\nIiought Sold Quoted\nStone,Prosser&Doty\n52 William St.. N. T. Hanover 7733\npii j\nSafe Bond$ for Investment\nHALSEY, STUART\nCO. Inc.\ntr-f n i rr-nrxT?- r\nPacific Coast\nCommon Stock\nJ. K. Rice, Jr.& Co.\ngM to mi\" r 80 wan l. M t\nj\nDIVIDENDS PASSED\nBY INTERNATIONAL\nImport and Export Corporation\nEarns $6 011 Common,\nbut AViil Conserve\nDIG LOSSES AKE DENIED\nAdvances to Affiliated Trading\nConcerns Ties Up Large\nSums of Money\n\nDirectors of the American International\nCorporation voted yesterday to\npass the regular quarterly dividends of\nj $1.50 a share on th _ common and preferred\nstocks. This statement was issued\nby the directors:\n\"The American International Corporation,\nIn pursuance of the purposes for\nwhich it was organized, IS engaged to\na large extent, through its subsidiaries,\nin foreign trade and commerce. In\nconsequence of the exceptional circumstances\nand requirements at this time\nthe board of directors, at their meeting\nto-day voted to omit the quarterly dividend\non the stock of the corporation.\"\nCharles A. Stone, president of the\ncorporation, said: 'Statements that the\nAmerican International Corporation has\nmade large losses In South America or\nanywhere else are untrue. v The omisj\nslon of the quarterly dividehd is part\nI of a conservative policy to husband the\nresources of the corporation.\"\nThe American international Corpora I\ntion, of which Frank A. Yandcrlip is\nchairman of the board, was organized\nin November, 1915, for the development\nof export and Import tra'de. It has\na capital of *59,000.000, of which *49,000,000\nis common and *1,00#,000 preferred.\nAn initial dividend on the common\nstock of 75 cents a share was paid on\nDecember 30, 1916, which rate was continued\nuntil December 31, 1917. From\nthen until June 30. 1919, regular quarterly\ndividends of 90 cents a share were\npaid. The rate was increased on June\n30, 1919, to *1.30 a share and on December\n31, 1919, to *1.50, which was\ncontinued until yesterday.\nThe corporation controls O. Amslnck\nCo., Carter, Macy Co. and the Allied\nMachinery Company of America.\nBesides it is a heavy stockholder in\nUnited Fruit, Pacific Mall Steamship\nand International Mercantile Marine.\nThe New York Shipbuilding Company.\nwhich the corporation owns, built 122\nships for the United States Government\nat Hog Island during the war.\nOfficials of the corporation declare J\nthat earnings for the current year on\nal; of Its ventures will equal *6 a share I\non the common stock, but that the company\nhas such a large volume of money\ntied up in advances to trading concerns\nwith which It Is affiliated that it was\ndecided to conserve its cash resources.\nPORPHYRY COMPANIES LOSE.\nNevada Consolidated and Ray\nConsolidated Report Deficits.\nTwo of the four porphyry topper companies,\nthe Nevada Consolidated Copper\nCompany and the Ray Consolidated Copper\nCompany, issued yesterday their reports\nfor the third quarter of 1920 and\nboth of them showed deficits in contrast\nto profits In the corresponding 1919\nquarter. The report of the Nevada comi\npany revealed a deficit, after charges\nand depreciation, of $83,180. In the\npreceding quarter it reported a profit of\n$384,000, and in the corresponding 1919\nquarter a profit of $464,449. Operating\nlosses after depreciation were $434,044,\nagainst operating profits of $331,154 in 1\nthe corresponding 1919 period. Other\nlricomo amounted to $350,864, against\n$133,295, ana dividends were $499,864\nagainst $749,796, leaving a final deficit t(\nfor the quarter of $583,044, against a\ndeficit a year ago of $285,347.\nThe Ray company report showed a net\noperating loss of $118,519 against a jij\nprofit of $706,071 In the corresponding 4i\n1919 quarter. Other income was $61,370\nAfiratnst 1226.076 and dividends were\n1394,294 against 1788,690, leaving a final Ii\ndeficit of $446,443 In contrast to a sur- j1\nplus of $143,557 In the third 1919 quar-\nter. v\nP\nMAXWELL-CHALMERS. l\nIleorgnniaatlon Plan la to Be lie-' c\nolnred Operative Soon.\na\nThe committee for the Maxwell Motor\nCompany, Inc., and the Chalmers Motor k\nCorporation annpunced yesterday that l<\nthe plan of September 1, 1920, looking J;\nto the reorganization nnd combination of\nthose two properties In all probability c\nsoon would be declared operative. More C;\nthan 83 per cent, of the outstanding Jj;\nshares of the two companies and more e\nthan 95 per cent, of the estimated C\namount of unsecured notes and accounts j,'\nof merchandise creditors have been deposited\nunder the plan, which by avert- j ci\nIng forced liquidation and providing a CI\nsubstantial amount of new money will\nmake placing the combined properties a\nIn a position of sound financial strength ji\npossible. J'\nBelieving that In view of the clrcum- I j]\nstances the small minority of unasjent- jj\nIre to avail themselves of the atlvan- U\ntares of the plan the commltteo nn- .j\nnounced yesterday a further extension of m\ntime until the close of business on No- K\nvember 27 for deposit of notes and\nclaims with the Central Union Trust\nCompany and for exercise by stockhold- w\ners of their minimum rights of purchase\nof new stock on equal terms with the\nsyndicate underwriters. Al\nAl\nCITIES SERVICE DIVIDEND. -J\nAI\nA\nDirectors Decide to Declare Only A\nAl\ntegular Disbursement*. J Al\nThe Cities Service Company declared 'V\nyesterday the regular monthly dividend* A\nof H of 1 per cont on Its preferred, a\npreference B end common stock. The\nregular monthly stock dividend of lit\nper cent, on Its common stock was also Ai\ndeclared. All of these dividends nre to A\nbe paid on January 1 to stock of record a,\nDecember l.r>. Following the directors' Al\nmeeting the following statement con- A'\ncernlng the company's dividend policy A]\nwas Issued: A\n\"At the meeting of the board of dlrec-\nI tors the question of sn Increase in the\nregular dividend on the common stock,\npayable In common stock at par, was\ndiscussed. The board was of the opinion\nthat the condition of the compnny,\nthe earning power of subsidiaries, toei\nther with the business outlook of the\ncompany for 1921, amply Justified an\nincrease In the stock dividend However,\ntaking Into consideration the gen\noriw Duiiiii-\"' nnu unnnnni TOiraiunnn j\nnow prevailing throughout the country. r\ntogether with the expressed opinion of I\na large number of stockholders of the\ncompany, the bonrd decided to make no i t.\nIncrease at this time, the policy being 1\nto continue payment of the regular j\nmonthly divldcnda on the common storit\nna during 1920 at the rate of fi per cent,\nannually In cash and 15 per cent, an- i\nnually In common stork at par.\"\nPARIS IIOI USE STEADY.\nPaSIS, Nov. 18.?Prices were barely\nsteady on the Bourse to-day. Three per f.\"\ncent, rentes, 85 francs 10 centimes. Ex- a?\nchange on London, 56 francs 85 centimes. Ho\nFive per cent loan, 83 francs 20 ccn-\ntimes. The dollar was quoted at It t-'\"\nfrancs 21 Vi centimes. Hp\n:\":v\nTHE N\nNEW ISSUE\n$57!\nDurham, No\n5!4%\nDated July 1, 1920 Due s<\nCoupon bonds in denominatio\nregistration in full o\nPrincipal and Interest (Jar\nU. S. Mortgage T\nFINANCIAL\nAssessed va uation\nTotal Bonded Debt\nLess Water Debt $8!\nLess Sinking Fund.. 3i\nNET DEBT\nPopulation, 192(\nPR!\n$16,000\n16,000\n16,000 annually\n24,000\n24,000 annually\n24,000\n32,000 annually\n39,000\n40,000 annually\nLegal opinion of Chester h\nCircular\nEstabroc\n24 Broad Street\nNew York\nPROVIDENCE\nExempt from All Fi\n$211\nCity of Sioux Fa\nIndependent\n5y2% School\nDated Doc. 1, 1920. Dcnomina\nlYInclpal and seml-ai\nand Decmebcr l) pays\nFinancial\nTotal llfhti Including this Issue\nSinking Fund\nNet Debt\nPopulation. to JO. t.in\nTOTAI. DEIST EESh THAN TWO\nI .\"guilty of issue\nMeurs. CIiopnuin.\nPrice 103.07,\n\nP. W. CHAI\n53 William Sti\nI CHICAGO\nThe above statements were obtained\nami while we do nrt guarantee t\nBID AND ASK\nV. STOCK EXCH